05604nam a22006975i 9780226820149DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021054318  a9780226820149  a(DE-B1597)626902  a(OCoLC)1330602990  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQ175.5b.B55 2022 4aQ175.5b.B55 2022 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a306.4/5223/eng/202201121 aBlair-Loy, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMisconceiving Merit :bParadoxes of Excellence and Devotion in Academic Science and Engineering /cMary Blair-Loy, Erin A. Cech. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b15 line drawings, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tOne. Misperceiving Merit, Excellence, and Devotion in Academic STEM -- tTwo. The Cultural Construction of Merit in Academic STEM -- tThree. The Work Devotion Schema and Its Consequences -- tFour. Mismeasuring Merit: The Schema of Scientific Excellence as a Yardstick of Merit -- tFive. Defending the Schema of Scientific Excellence, Defending Inequality -- tSix. The Moralization of Merit: Consequences for Scientists and Science -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn incisive study showing how cultural ideas of merit in academic science produce unfair and unequal outcomes. In Misconceiving Merit, sociologists Mary Blair-Loy and Erin A. Cech uncover the cultural foundations of a paradox. On one hand, academic science, engineering, and math revere meritocracy, a system that recognizes and rewards those with the greatest talent and dedication. At the same time, women and some racial and sexual minorities remain underrepresented and often feel unwelcome and devalued in STEM. How can academic science, which so highly values meritocracy and objectivity, produce these unequal outcomes? Blair-Loy and Cech studied more than five hundred STEM professors at a top research university to reveal how unequal and unfair outcomes can emerge alongside commitments to objectivity and excellence. The authors find that academic STEM harbors dominant cultural beliefs that not only perpetuate the mistreatment of scientists from underrepresented groups but hinder innovation. Underrepresented groups are often seen as less fully embodying merit compared to equally productive white and Asian heterosexual men, and the negative consequences of this misjudgment persist regardless of professors’ actual academic productivity. Misconceiving Merit is filled with insights for higher education administrators working toward greater equity as well as for scientists and engineers striving to change entrenched patterns of inequality in STEM.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCollege teacherszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aDiscrimination in higher education. 0aScience teacherszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 0aScientistsxRating of. 0aScientistszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aWork-life balance. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  ameritocracy, stem, gender, race, equality, equity, diversity, inclusion, science, engineering, math, merit, minorities, marginalization, objectivity, research university, professors, faculty, advising, innovation, productivity, mistreatment, perception, stereotypes, bias, discrimination, prejudice, performance, nonfiction, sociology, higher education, college, training, promotion, career, profession.1 aCech, Erin A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz9783110